         <entryFree xml:id="k000294" type="architectural feature">
            <term xml:id="term-k000294-1" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin-nt">cheshangmingzao</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000294-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">徹上明造</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000294-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">彻上明造</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000294-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">chèshàngmíngzào</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000294-5" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile">ch`e-shang-ming-tsao</term>
            <idno type="URI">https://architecturasinica.org/keyword/k000294</idno>
            <note type="Note">
               <p>under construction</p>
               <p xml:lan="en">The term cheshang mingzao 徹上明造 appears exclusively in the Yingzao fashi (Li 2009, 4.6a, 5.2a, 5.3a, 5.6b). Literally “fully-visible construction,” 
                  the character che 徹 means “to penetrate,” while cheshang 徹上 indicates “thoroughness” or “completeness.” The term ming 明 denotes “visible” or “illuminated” and zao 造 
                  is any method of construction. [2] Combined, the terms refer to a traditional Chinese architectural practice where all structural components of the interior ceiling are 
                  visible. When this technique is employed, the finishing of the beam framework requires meticulous craftsmanship. </p>
               <p xml:lan="en">Scholars generally agree that cheshang mingzao refers to the complete visibility of the interior structural framework of the roof [Liang 3]; Pan and He [4]; 
                  Chen [5]; Fu [6]). However, in practice, it is common to find examples where some structural elements are exposed while others are concealed behind a ceiling. 
                  Contemporary scholars often use both “cheshang mingzao” and “pingqi” 平棊 in their descriptions of exposed interior frames [7], even though this is often misleading given 
                  the original meaning of “complete exposure.” Contemporary scholars have introduced the neologism cheshang lumingzao 徹上露明造 [8]（Liang 2006, 5) (sometimes abbreviated to 
                  lumingzao 露明造) as synonyms for cheshang mingzao.</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">“徹上明造”一詞僅見于宋《營造法式》（Li 2009, 4.6a,5.2a,5.3a,5.6b），指中國古代建築室內頂部全部構架顯露可見的做法。當使用徹上明造時，梁架構件需做精緻處理。“徹”是通的意思，
                  “徹上”表示貫通，通達。（漢語大詞典2.0電子版2002） “明”，指顯露。學界共識是“徹上明造”室內構架應全部可見（梁思成 1983, 109；潘谷西和何建中 2005, 251；陳明达 1021, 401；傅熹年 2009, 534）。
                  實例中常見部分顯露，部分有天花的情況。當代學者會同時使用“徹上明造”及平棊等加以描述（侯幼彬 、李婉貞，2002：90），但這與徹上明造全部露明的意思存在矛盾。當代文獻中又有 “徹上露明造” （梁思成，2006：5）、
                  “露明造"，均為當代學者新創造的術語。</p>                 
            </note>
